Idea: Metal capable of storing memories it "witnesses" via reflections. The more memories it stores, the more it hardens. Can replay memories through reflections when polished with sentience. The oldest Reminsteel will always be stronger than the youngest Reminsteel, regardless of how much the process and creation method is refined.

Additional Chatty Notes:
Remnisteel behaves as a reflective mnemonic alloy capable of storing impressions of events witnessed through its mirrored surfaces.

Unlike normal memory storage materials, Remnisteel does not simply record visuals. It stores emotional atmosphere, conceptual weight, and psychological residue associated with observed events.

As the material accumulates memories over centuries, it becomes progressively denser and more durable. Because older Remnisteel contains longer chains of accumulated historical memory, age itself becomes one of the alloy's greatest strengthening factors.

This creates an unusual phenomenon where ancient imperfect Remnisteel can outperform newly-forged "superior" variants purely due to experiential accumulation.

When polished using Sentience-reactive compounds, reflections upon Remnisteel surfaces may replay fragmented memories witnessed by the metal itself.